WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:02.040
All right.

00:00:02.040 --> 00:00:04.920
Who here has ever opened a dashboard

00:00:04.920 --> 00:00:08.200
with 18 or more filters spread across six tabs

00:00:08.200 --> 00:00:10.400
and wondered what you were even looking at?

00:00:12.520 --> 00:00:14.440
Let's see some hands, right?

00:00:14.440 --> 00:00:17.680
Now I want you to imagine that you're not a data scientist,

00:00:17.680 --> 00:00:20.200
right, you're an executive who has to make a decision

00:00:20.200 --> 00:00:23.400
in the next 10 minutes, right?

00:00:23.400 --> 00:00:25.480
This might be you frantically clicking around,

00:00:25.480 --> 00:00:27.040
trying to make sense of things,

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:31.360
or maybe you have some bigger feelings, right?

00:00:31.360 --> 00:00:33.160
Truth is, we've all probably been there, right,

00:00:33.160 --> 00:00:34.959
and it never feels good.

00:00:34.959 --> 00:00:37.240
So, welcome to my dashboard support group.

00:00:37.240 --> 00:00:38.799
Let's do a quick check-in.

00:00:38.799 --> 00:00:40.759
Raise your hand if you've ever designed a UI

00:00:40.759 --> 00:00:44.240
with more than 10 filters, drop-downs, toggles, whatever.

00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:47.520
Keep them up if you've gone over 20.

00:00:48.959 --> 00:00:50.279
Nice.

00:00:50.279 --> 00:00:52.080
All right, how about this?

00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:55.959
Who's ever had a client ask for just one more drop-down

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:57.959
when you knew it was gonna be too much?

00:00:59.520 --> 00:01:01.560
All right, if you're nodding along to this,

00:01:01.560 --> 00:01:03.919
no judgment here, you're among friends.

00:01:03.919 --> 00:01:06.879
My name is Jeremy, and I've been there, too.

00:01:06.879 --> 00:01:08.199
I'm a psychologist by training,

00:01:08.199 --> 00:01:10.040
but probably not the type that comes to mind

00:01:10.040 --> 00:01:10.959
when I say that.

00:01:12.320 --> 00:01:14.080
A lot of folks, when they think about psychology,

00:01:14.080 --> 00:01:16.040
they think about couches and therapy,

00:01:16.040 --> 00:01:18.879
but the field itself is really driven by data.

00:01:18.879 --> 00:01:20.760
And my journey took me from studying

00:01:20.760 --> 00:01:22.839
how groups make decisions under pressure

00:01:22.839 --> 00:01:26.040
to accidentally designing systems that cause that pressure

00:01:26.040 --> 00:01:28.360
to then figuring out how we can fix them.

00:01:28.360 --> 00:01:30.239
And after years of building dashboards

00:01:30.239 --> 00:01:31.559
that were technically great,

00:01:31.559 --> 00:01:34.980
but didn't quite land with users, I had this realization.

00:01:36.160 --> 00:01:38.279
A lot of dashboard failures aren't technical.

00:01:38.279 --> 00:01:39.919
They're psychological.

00:01:39.919 --> 00:01:41.480
They don't fail because of the wrong chart type

00:01:41.480 --> 00:01:42.919
or the wrong database.

00:01:42.919 --> 00:01:45.839
They fail because we're making them for humans,

00:01:45.839 --> 00:01:47.480
and humans are complicated.

00:01:47.480 --> 00:01:49.400
But we can engineer for psychology

00:01:49.400 --> 00:01:52.239
just as much as we engineer for performance.

00:01:52.519 --> 00:01:54.599
Let me show you what I mean.

00:01:54.599 --> 00:01:57.120
This is a dashboard from a client of mine.

00:01:57.120 --> 00:01:58.400
Details blinded, of course,

00:01:58.400 --> 00:02:01.800
but they had built a really impressive dashboard themselves.

00:02:01.800 --> 00:02:04.400
They had lots of filters, customized views,

00:02:04.400 --> 00:02:05.279
and despite what you see here,

00:02:05.279 --> 00:02:07.099
they actually had some really cool visualizations

00:02:07.099 --> 00:02:09.119
buried in some of their deep dives.

00:02:09.119 --> 00:02:10.559
The client loved it.

00:02:10.559 --> 00:02:13.360
Users could analyze anything they wanted,

00:02:13.360 --> 00:02:14.839
except they never did.

00:02:14.839 --> 00:02:15.679
They opened the app,

00:02:15.679 --> 00:02:17.800
and shortly after, they completely deserted it

00:02:17.800 --> 00:02:20.080
and found creative workarounds like Excel.

00:02:20.919 --> 00:02:25.139
So, we collected some telemetry data for about 30 days,

00:02:25.139 --> 00:02:27.119
and just to kind of get an idea

00:02:27.119 --> 00:02:29.559
of what people were doing with the dashboard.

00:02:29.559 --> 00:02:30.919
We rolled this out in a minor update

00:02:30.919 --> 00:02:33.240
to get some users engaged in just to see

00:02:33.240 --> 00:02:36.320
what they were actually doing with the application.

00:02:36.320 --> 00:02:39.600
And it painted this user journey clip of despair here.

00:02:40.559 --> 00:02:43.240
95% of users, they opened the URL.

00:02:43.240 --> 00:02:44.839
Fantastic, they were really interested in it,

00:02:44.839 --> 00:02:46.639
even though they'd seen this dashboard before,

00:02:46.639 --> 00:02:49.559
and we told them it was just a minor update.

00:02:49.559 --> 00:02:52.199
88% went further, actually opened the dashboard,

00:02:52.199 --> 00:02:54.179
so they got past that landing page.

00:02:54.179 --> 00:02:56.320
But this is where things get brutal.

00:02:56.320 --> 00:03:00.259
About half only used one filter, just one.

00:03:01.160 --> 00:03:04.520
And about a fifth returned after a week.

00:03:05.399 --> 00:03:07.479
So, this chart is screaming at us,

00:03:07.479 --> 00:03:08.960
stop doing this to your users.

00:03:08.960 --> 00:03:10.639
Something is wrong here.

00:03:10.639 --> 00:03:13.000
But how do we know what that is?

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:15.479
Well, with behavioral science,

00:03:15.479 --> 00:03:19.500
which is the study of how people think, feel, and act.

00:03:20.279 --> 00:03:22.259
Typically in the context of decision making.

00:03:22.259 --> 00:03:23.820
But across decades of research,

00:03:23.820 --> 00:03:26.139
what we find is that people are rational,

00:03:26.139 --> 00:03:28.899
but in surprisingly predictable ways.

00:03:28.899 --> 00:03:31.380
And so for us as developers, this is actually good news,

00:03:31.380 --> 00:03:34.660
because we can understand that strange user behavior

00:03:34.660 --> 00:03:36.119
of ours and design for it.

00:03:37.220 --> 00:03:40.339
So here's a classic study to illustrate what I mean here.

00:03:40.339 --> 00:03:43.100
Researchers set up a tasting test at a grocery store

00:03:43.100 --> 00:03:44.940
and varied the number of jams that they had

00:03:44.940 --> 00:03:47.100
on display at this table.

00:03:47.100 --> 00:03:48.380
And in the big display condition,

00:03:48.380 --> 00:03:50.380
there were 24 jams on the table.

00:03:50.380 --> 00:03:53.779
In the small display condition, there were only six jams.

00:03:53.779 --> 00:03:57.179
And the big display with 24 jams

00:03:57.179 --> 00:03:59.300
actually attracted more shoppers.

00:03:59.300 --> 00:04:00.820
60% of people stopped,

00:04:00.820 --> 00:04:04.100
whereas only 40% of people stopped in the small condition.

00:04:04.100 --> 00:04:07.419
But only 3% of people in that large condition

00:04:07.419 --> 00:04:08.600
actually bought jam,

00:04:08.600 --> 00:04:12.380
whereas 30% did in the small condition.

00:04:12.380 --> 00:04:14.860
So that's a convergent difference of 10 times.

00:04:15.740 --> 00:04:17.459
And so this is exactly what's going on

00:04:17.459 --> 00:04:18.500
with our dashboards, right?

00:04:18.500 --> 00:04:21.619
We're seeing more features and more options

00:04:21.619 --> 00:04:24.559
attract attention, but paralyze choice.

00:04:25.559 --> 00:04:29.619
And so paradox of choice is one key component here,

00:04:29.619 --> 00:04:32.040
but there's a lot of concepts in behavioral science

00:04:32.040 --> 00:04:35.140
that we can pull from that are applicable to dashboards.

00:04:35.140 --> 00:04:36.260
We don't have time to go through all of them,

00:04:36.260 --> 00:04:38.339
I'm just gonna pull out some common themes here,

00:04:38.339 --> 00:04:39.899
just talk really high level about them,

00:04:39.899 --> 00:04:41.959
because they're not just abstract theories.

00:04:41.959 --> 00:04:43.140
These are engineering principles

00:04:43.140 --> 00:04:45.279
that we can leverage in our dashboards.

00:04:45.279 --> 00:04:46.579
Cognitive load, for example, right?

00:04:46.579 --> 00:04:49.220
This is how having too many choices

00:04:49.220 --> 00:04:51.899
can actually overwhelm our mental capacity.

00:04:51.899 --> 00:04:53.040
So think of this like RAM.

00:04:53.040 --> 00:04:55.179
Your users have processing limits,

00:04:55.179 --> 00:04:58.920
and each filter adds a processing cost.

00:04:59.940 --> 00:05:01.619
Progressive disclosure is the idea

00:05:01.619 --> 00:05:03.500
that we're kind of hiding complexity

00:05:03.500 --> 00:05:05.299
until it's actually needed, right?

00:05:05.299 --> 00:05:07.500
And so we're showing that vital information first,

00:05:07.500 --> 00:05:09.260
those key points up first,

00:05:09.260 --> 00:05:11.299
and then just revealing more later on.

00:05:11.299 --> 00:05:14.220
It's kind of like lazy loading for human cognition.

00:05:14.220 --> 00:05:15.059
And then for immunoflex,

00:05:15.059 --> 00:05:17.220
I'll show you a more concrete example of this,

00:05:17.220 --> 00:05:19.339
but this is how basically the same exact data

00:05:19.339 --> 00:05:22.019
can show two very different stories.

00:05:22.019 --> 00:05:25.140
So revenue being up 15% might be a true statement,

00:05:25.140 --> 00:05:25.980
but it could also be true

00:05:25.980 --> 00:05:28.220
that it's missing the target by 5%.

00:05:28.220 --> 00:05:30.359
And so unless folks are talking about that,

00:05:30.359 --> 00:05:33.220
they might be coming from two very different places.

00:05:33.220 --> 00:05:35.440
And so when we apply this to dashboards,

00:05:35.440 --> 00:05:37.980
this might mean showing three filters

00:05:37.980 --> 00:05:39.779
instead of all 18 at first.

00:05:39.779 --> 00:05:41.420
It might mean showing summaries

00:05:41.420 --> 00:05:43.660
instead of those detailed outputs, right?

00:05:43.660 --> 00:05:46.019
And so this is how we start to engineer

00:05:46.019 --> 00:05:47.679
for the user experience.

00:05:48.739 --> 00:05:50.579
But what if you don't know anything

00:05:50.579 --> 00:05:52.540
about behavioral science, right?

00:05:52.540 --> 00:05:54.339
Well, you fall back on things

00:05:54.339 --> 00:05:56.500
that you do know something about.

00:05:56.500 --> 00:05:58.700
And I bet you'd know a little something about road trips,

00:05:58.700 --> 00:06:01.299
especially if you took the road trip here, right?

00:06:01.299 --> 00:06:03.619
And so engineering apps with behavioral science

00:06:03.619 --> 00:06:05.660
is a lot like planning for a road trip.

00:06:05.660 --> 00:06:07.140
You need to know your destination,

00:06:07.140 --> 00:06:08.859
you need to anticipate the hazards,

00:06:08.859 --> 00:06:11.459
and you need to make sure everyone arrives there safely.

00:06:11.459 --> 00:06:13.540
Right, and that's where the behavioral insight design

00:06:14.420 --> 00:06:16.179
or the bid framework, right?

00:06:16.179 --> 00:06:18.820
The five simple stages that guide you through this process

00:06:18.820 --> 00:06:20.579
and help prevent those dashboard disasters

00:06:20.579 --> 00:06:22.100
that we've all seen.

00:06:22.100 --> 00:06:24.320
And what makes this different from other UX advice

00:06:24.320 --> 00:06:27.579
is that it's a concrete step-by-step framework

00:06:27.579 --> 00:06:29.660
built on decades of research.

00:06:29.660 --> 00:06:32.059
And each stage builds into the next,

00:06:32.059 --> 00:06:34.660
so this provides this continuous feedback loop

00:06:34.660 --> 00:06:36.559
that helps you keep improving your dashboard

00:06:36.559 --> 00:06:38.279
whenever you'd like to revisit that.

00:06:38.279 --> 00:06:40.500
Plus, the whole thing is bundled into an R package,

00:06:40.500 --> 00:06:42.100
so it does levy lifting for you.

00:06:43.100 --> 00:06:45.179
So meet BidUX, right?

00:06:45.179 --> 00:06:47.820
It's designed specifically for our workflows

00:06:47.820 --> 00:06:49.220
as Shiny developers,

00:06:49.220 --> 00:06:51.299
and it works with any dashboard that you've already built.

00:06:51.299 --> 00:06:53.859
So you don't need to refactor, no need to start over.

00:06:53.859 --> 00:06:55.619
If you have telemetry data, that's great.

00:06:55.619 --> 00:06:57.260
It'll actually analyze that data

00:06:57.260 --> 00:06:59.279
and give you data-driven insights.

00:06:59.279 --> 00:07:01.059
But if you don't have any telemetry data,

00:07:01.059 --> 00:07:03.579
you can still just use simple verbal descriptions

00:07:03.579 --> 00:07:06.660
based on what you've seen or what your users have reported.

00:07:06.660 --> 00:07:08.059
But whatever inputs you provide,

00:07:08.059 --> 00:07:11.220
it will use those to auto-suggest improvements

00:07:11.220 --> 00:07:13.459
based on the available research.

00:07:14.299 --> 00:07:16.839
Think of it as having a behavioral science in your console.

00:07:16.839 --> 00:07:18.820
Always available, never judges,

00:07:18.820 --> 00:07:20.380
and doesn't charge by the hour.

00:07:21.299 --> 00:07:24.100
So let me show you what this process actually looks like.

00:07:26.739 --> 00:07:28.380
So first we start with the interpret stage,

00:07:28.380 --> 00:07:30.220
the why behind the dashboard,

00:07:30.220 --> 00:07:32.339
because the central question here

00:07:32.339 --> 00:07:34.820
is really what's driving the focus for your users.

00:07:34.820 --> 00:07:38.100
It's what they're coming to the dashboard for

00:07:38.100 --> 00:07:39.100
in the first place.

00:07:40.059 --> 00:07:42.500
And that data story helps create

00:07:42.500 --> 00:07:44.220
the narrative structure for this.

00:07:44.220 --> 00:07:47.019
So humans are hardwired for stories, not pivot tables.

00:07:47.899 --> 00:07:50.980
Context, the hook, tension, resolution,

00:07:50.980 --> 00:07:53.339
all of this is the structure that folks are looking for

00:07:53.339 --> 00:07:54.540
with their key insights.

00:07:54.540 --> 00:07:56.500
And so we build that in from the start.

00:07:57.940 --> 00:08:00.660
And then finally, users and personas help us developers

00:08:00.660 --> 00:08:02.179
take that user perspective.

00:08:03.059 --> 00:08:06.059
Project manager probably doesn't think in SQL terms.

00:08:06.059 --> 00:08:07.700
They think in business outcomes.

00:08:07.700 --> 00:08:10.899
So we need to make sure the dashboard bridges that gap.

00:08:12.540 --> 00:08:13.940
And then putting all of that together,

00:08:13.940 --> 00:08:16.100
the function will summarize that

00:08:16.100 --> 00:08:18.200
and let you know if you're missing any information.

00:08:18.200 --> 00:08:20.019
And if you are, it's probably a good time to go back

00:08:20.019 --> 00:08:20.980
and check in with your client,

00:08:20.980 --> 00:08:22.760
make sure you're considering their perspective,

00:08:22.760 --> 00:08:25.480
because when we neglect that context,

00:08:25.480 --> 00:08:28.660
we end up building friction points into our user interfaces.

00:08:30.260 --> 00:08:33.700
Which is what the second stage, notice, is about.

00:08:33.700 --> 00:08:35.539
So going back to my client's dashboard,

00:08:35.539 --> 00:08:37.320
this is a summary of the telemetry data

00:08:37.940 --> 00:08:39.960
we collected on the filter usage.

00:08:39.960 --> 00:08:42.679
So 14 filters here, hardly ever used.

00:08:42.679 --> 00:08:45.840
And half of those were hardly even touched.

00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:48.359
So this is technical debt visualized.

00:08:48.359 --> 00:08:51.440
Each unused filter, that's maintenance overhead.

00:08:51.440 --> 00:08:52.919
There might even be database queries running

00:08:52.919 --> 00:08:55.679
on the back end for those unused filters.

00:08:55.679 --> 00:08:58.159
And so this is why the notice stage

00:08:58.159 --> 00:09:00.280
focuses on finding those friction points.

00:09:01.640 --> 00:09:03.979
The package auto-suggests relevant behavioral theories

00:09:03.979 --> 00:09:05.039
with confidence scores.

00:09:05.039 --> 00:09:07.760
So in this case, it's suggesting cognitive load theory

00:09:07.760 --> 00:09:10.000
with a 90% confidence score.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:12.280
But it might also suggest choice overload

00:09:12.280 --> 00:09:13.840
or decision fatigue.

00:09:13.840 --> 00:09:16.599
It depends on the context from those users or personas

00:09:16.599 --> 00:09:19.659
and what you're feeding into it at this stage.

00:09:19.659 --> 00:09:23.159
It starts to transform that user feedback of it's confusing

00:09:23.159 --> 00:09:26.119
into something more specific, like an engineering principle

00:09:26.119 --> 00:09:28.359
of cognitive load exceeding working memory.

00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:30.440
So you're not guessing anymore,

00:09:30.440 --> 00:09:32.559
you're addressing identified psychological barriers

00:09:32.559 --> 00:09:33.539
with code changes.

00:09:35.440 --> 00:09:38.640
The package will also suggest bias mitigations

00:09:38.640 --> 00:09:40.880
based on the dashboard context and personas.

00:09:40.880 --> 00:09:43.760
So again, using that previous stage information,

00:09:43.760 --> 00:09:46.760
it will suggest specific information processing biases.

00:09:46.760 --> 00:09:49.400
And also specific ways to mitigate them.

00:09:50.479 --> 00:09:52.359
So in this case, we're getting an anchoring,

00:09:52.359 --> 00:09:54.520
framing, confirmation bias.

00:09:54.520 --> 00:09:56.559
And these are all bugs that it's identifying

00:09:56.559 --> 00:09:57.840
in human cognition.

00:09:57.840 --> 00:10:01.080
And these are bugs that affect every user in some capacity.

00:10:01.080 --> 00:10:03.320
But now we can start to guard for them.

00:10:03.320 --> 00:10:06.200
So in my client's case, we had multiple stakeholders

00:10:06.200 --> 00:10:07.880
who were coming from different teams

00:10:07.880 --> 00:10:09.140
with different perspectives.

00:10:09.140 --> 00:10:11.380
And so we focused a lot on framing effects.

00:10:12.400 --> 00:10:15.599
And so in this case, we had added a toggle.

00:10:15.599 --> 00:10:17.880
In the progress or the gain frame,

00:10:17.880 --> 00:10:19.500
this was showing that relative difference

00:10:19.500 --> 00:10:22.840
between the raw value and the client's benchmark.

00:10:22.840 --> 00:10:24.640
And so this was highlighting the achievements

00:10:24.640 --> 00:10:27.320
that the marketing team was interested in.

00:10:27.320 --> 00:10:31.760
But when we switched to a loss frame, or a gap frame,

00:10:31.760 --> 00:10:34.419
we're looking at the raw values versus that benchmark

00:10:34.419 --> 00:10:36.080
instead of the relative difference.

00:10:36.080 --> 00:10:38.599
And so now, this is looking more at the improvements

00:10:38.599 --> 00:10:39.960
that still need to be made.

00:10:39.960 --> 00:10:42.400
And so with this, we have the same data,

00:10:42.400 --> 00:10:44.119
but a very different story.

00:10:44.119 --> 00:10:46.559
This is proactive bugging for human psychology.

00:10:46.559 --> 00:10:48.760
Because now teams can coordinate and align

00:10:48.760 --> 00:10:49.960
on what they're actually seeing

00:10:49.960 --> 00:10:51.359
and what their concerns are.

00:10:53.280 --> 00:10:57.200
Okay, so at this point, we know what the dashboard's for.

00:10:57.200 --> 00:11:00.400
We've looked at the problems we need to fix.

00:11:00.400 --> 00:11:03.780
We've looked at the targeted biases to guard against.

00:11:03.780 --> 00:11:05.799
And now, it's time to put everything

00:11:05.799 --> 00:11:07.880
into a structured information flow.

00:11:07.880 --> 00:11:09.559
All right, and so using BidStructure,

00:11:09.559 --> 00:11:12.479
we can get specific implementation suggestions.

00:11:12.479 --> 00:11:14.440
Not just reduce complexity,

00:11:14.440 --> 00:11:17.479
but use BSLibAccordion for progressive disclosure,

00:11:17.479 --> 00:11:19.020
for example.

00:11:19.020 --> 00:11:21.880
The package shows which components

00:11:21.880 --> 00:11:23.880
should map to the theory.

00:11:23.880 --> 00:11:27.640
So it's tying specific functions from Shiny,

00:11:27.640 --> 00:11:29.479
from BSLib, from different packages

00:11:29.479 --> 00:11:31.719
that we might use to build into our workflows

00:11:31.719 --> 00:11:33.159
to these principles.

00:11:33.159 --> 00:11:35.799
And it gives multiple options and suggestions to try.

00:11:37.080 --> 00:11:39.780
So for example, see this F pattern here?

00:11:39.780 --> 00:11:43.320
This is how most users are scanning dashboards

00:11:43.320 --> 00:11:45.039
in Western cultures.

00:11:45.039 --> 00:11:47.419
Top left gets most of the attention.

00:11:47.419 --> 00:11:49.559
Bottom right might as well not exist.

00:11:49.559 --> 00:11:50.640
And so this structure stage

00:11:50.640 --> 00:11:53.280
is putting the most important information up front

00:11:53.280 --> 00:11:55.320
where the eyes will naturally go.

00:11:55.320 --> 00:11:57.960
So critical KPIs, summaries,

00:11:57.960 --> 00:11:59.440
those are placed at the top.

00:12:00.280 --> 00:12:01.599
The supporting details follow the F pattern,

00:12:01.599 --> 00:12:04.000
and deep dives progressively get disclosed

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:04.960
towards the bottom.

00:12:06.159 --> 00:12:11.159
And finally, from here, we get to the last stage.

00:12:11.479 --> 00:12:14.599
We'll feed this into our validation stage,

00:12:14.599 --> 00:12:17.400
where we validate not only what we've done,

00:12:17.400 --> 00:12:20.280
but we also look for ways to empower user engagement.

00:12:20.280 --> 00:12:22.520
So this helps you as the developer

00:12:22.520 --> 00:12:25.140
know whether the dashboard is working as intended,

00:12:25.140 --> 00:12:28.640
but also helps users know what to expect next.

00:12:28.640 --> 00:12:30.679
It'll guide developers through all the changes,

00:12:30.679 --> 00:12:33.520
through iterations, and it will also suggest,

00:12:33.520 --> 00:12:35.719
again, different ways of not only empowerment,

00:12:35.719 --> 00:12:37.840
but even collaborating between your users,

00:12:37.840 --> 00:12:39.799
your end users and teams.

00:12:39.799 --> 00:12:41.400
So for example, in this case,

00:12:41.400 --> 00:12:43.179
we looked at executive summaries,

00:12:43.179 --> 00:12:46.159
because this client had, again, a lot of different teams

00:12:46.159 --> 00:12:47.400
coming from different backgrounds,

00:12:47.400 --> 00:12:49.200
and they really wanted these key takeaways

00:12:49.200 --> 00:12:51.840
to be up and prominent.

00:12:51.840 --> 00:12:54.200
And so what we did is we looked at the executive summaries,

00:12:54.200 --> 00:12:55.440
we placed those at the top,

00:12:55.440 --> 00:12:57.719
and then we tailored them to the user personas.

00:12:57.719 --> 00:13:00.320
So for executives, they were a little bit more

00:13:00.320 --> 00:13:02.359
high-level, targeted, action-oriented.

00:13:02.359 --> 00:13:05.280
But for developers or analysts,

00:13:05.280 --> 00:13:07.000
those were a little bit more tech-oriented

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:08.559
and a little bit more low-level.

00:13:08.559 --> 00:13:12.580
And so this generates also other checklists after this

00:13:12.580 --> 00:13:15.960
to validate and also look for other accessibility checks

00:13:15.960 --> 00:13:17.960
to really help you as the developer guide

00:13:17.960 --> 00:13:20.159
and create those aha moments for your users.

00:13:21.039 --> 00:13:22.880
Validation isn't the last stage either.

00:13:22.880 --> 00:13:24.340
It can feed back into interpret,

00:13:24.340 --> 00:13:26.239
so creating that feedback loop.

00:13:26.239 --> 00:13:29.320
But let's take a moment and look at the transformation

00:13:29.320 --> 00:13:31.520
of my client's dashboard here.

00:13:31.520 --> 00:13:33.719
So here's the dashboard disaster again.

00:13:33.719 --> 00:13:36.239
Technically perfect, but psychologically broken.

00:13:36.239 --> 00:13:38.239
Had everything except for its own users.

00:13:39.119 --> 00:13:41.179
So let's see what behavioral science can do

00:13:41.179 --> 00:13:42.179
to turn this around.

00:13:43.799 --> 00:13:45.280
All right, here's the same dashboard,

00:13:45.280 --> 00:13:47.840
but with a transformed user experience.

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:49.799
We have clean executive summary at the top.

00:13:49.799 --> 00:13:51.280
Users know immediately what matters

00:13:51.280 --> 00:13:52.619
and what to do about it.

00:13:52.619 --> 00:13:55.440
We have progressive disclosure, complexity available,

00:13:55.479 --> 00:13:57.479
but isn't required.

00:13:57.479 --> 00:13:59.200
And if you want to get even more into the details,

00:13:59.200 --> 00:14:02.320
we have those further at the bottom end of the deep dives.

00:14:02.320 --> 00:14:03.960
We also have smart defaults that are based

00:14:03.960 --> 00:14:06.880
on actual usage patterns, not just assumptions.

00:14:06.880 --> 00:14:09.479
And we telemetry the data, so the before and after.

00:14:10.400 --> 00:14:12.880
We see filter usage up 38%.

00:14:12.880 --> 00:14:15.479
People are actually exploring instead of abandoning shit.

00:14:15.479 --> 00:14:17.000
Return rate up 75%.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:18.840
They're actually coming back now.

00:14:18.840 --> 00:14:21.280
And this is the ROI of behavioral science.

00:14:21.280 --> 00:14:24.159
It's not magic, it's not AI.

00:14:24.159 --> 00:14:27.840
It's designing for how human minds actually think.

00:14:27.840 --> 00:14:29.799
We're reducing that cognitive load,

00:14:29.799 --> 00:14:31.440
we're aligning with mental models,

00:14:31.440 --> 00:14:33.840
and we're creating a clear information hierarchy.

00:14:35.440 --> 00:14:38.080
That gives us more users, deeper engagement,

00:14:38.080 --> 00:14:40.719
and stronger retention, because we're removing obstacles

00:14:40.719 --> 00:14:42.960
instead of just adding features.

00:14:42.960 --> 00:14:45.919
And as a developer, that means less support tickets,

00:14:45.919 --> 00:14:47.919
less feature requests, because your users are starting

00:14:47.919 --> 00:14:51.359
to find what they need and figure it out on their own.

00:14:51.359 --> 00:14:54.320
It also might mean potentially better performance reviews,

00:14:54.320 --> 00:14:56.679
because now you're building products that are driving value.

00:14:56.679 --> 00:14:58.840
And that's really the difference between just building

00:14:58.840 --> 00:15:01.400
in features and building products that people love.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.440
And here are just some more results from other clients

00:15:06.440 --> 00:15:09.200
from the last year or so of when I've been integrating

00:15:09.200 --> 00:15:10.919
this BID framework here.

00:15:10.919 --> 00:15:12.520
And on average, we're just seeing people engage

00:15:12.520 --> 00:15:13.799
with the dashboard longer.

00:15:13.799 --> 00:15:15.559
It's performing better in general,

00:15:15.559 --> 00:15:16.719
and we're getting rid of unneeded,

00:15:16.719 --> 00:15:19.119
because we're getting rid of unneeded processes.

00:15:19.159 --> 00:15:21.520
And we're seeing more user traffic across the board.

00:15:21.520 --> 00:15:24.479
And this is just becoming effective across the board,

00:15:24.479 --> 00:15:25.599
across these different domains,

00:15:25.599 --> 00:15:28.159
because human psychology is predictable,

00:15:28.159 --> 00:15:31.760
even as irrational as it might be at times.

00:15:31.760 --> 00:15:34.059
Your finance users have the same working memory slots

00:15:34.059 --> 00:15:36.679
as your healthcare users, and so this framework adapts

00:15:36.679 --> 00:15:38.599
to different domains, because the principles

00:15:38.599 --> 00:15:40.719
remain consistent across those domains.

00:15:42.580 --> 00:15:44.340
And here's the really nice part.

00:15:44.340 --> 00:15:47.940
Implementing this psychology is just a few lines of code.

00:15:47.940 --> 00:15:49.500
If you have telemetry, simply load it

00:15:49.500 --> 00:15:51.640
with the BID telemetry function.

00:15:51.640 --> 00:15:54.500
And then here, I'm just filtering down

00:15:54.500 --> 00:15:56.719
to one of the critical issues identified,

00:15:56.719 --> 00:15:58.659
and then adding the central question

00:15:58.659 --> 00:16:00.700
to contextualize everything that follows.

00:16:02.500 --> 00:16:04.320
Then I use BID notice.

00:16:04.320 --> 00:16:05.559
It's a BID notice issue.

00:16:05.559 --> 00:16:08.059
It's a bridge function for the telemetry data

00:16:08.059 --> 00:16:11.020
that will feed and populate the following stages.

00:16:12.260 --> 00:16:15.119
From there, it's just running through the rest of the steps,

00:16:15.119 --> 00:16:17.340
and optionally ending with BID report.

00:16:17.340 --> 00:16:19.380
This will create a markdown report for PR,

00:16:19.380 --> 00:16:21.780
for documentation, whatever your needs might be.

00:16:22.940 --> 00:16:24.260
Now, if you don't have telemetry data,

00:16:24.260 --> 00:16:26.580
that's not a problem either, because you can simply

00:16:26.580 --> 00:16:28.820
fill it in manually based on your observations

00:16:28.820 --> 00:16:29.960
or user feedback.

00:16:30.900 --> 00:16:32.940
So, start by creating your data story

00:16:32.940 --> 00:16:34.900
to structure the dashboard's narrative.

00:16:36.500 --> 00:16:38.780
Identify the friction points, because even without data,

00:16:38.780 --> 00:16:40.640
you probably know where your users are struggling

00:16:40.640 --> 00:16:41.479
to some extent.

00:16:43.020 --> 00:16:44.700
And we have that same five-stage pipeline

00:16:44.700 --> 00:16:46.619
with the same actual insights.

00:16:47.700 --> 00:16:50.059
And this BID report function can generate markdown,

00:16:50.059 --> 00:16:53.219
can generate text, or HTML, depending on your needs.

00:16:53.219 --> 00:16:56.380
But this overall framework is really guiding you

00:16:56.380 --> 00:16:58.419
whether you have a lot of telemetry data

00:16:58.419 --> 00:17:00.479
or just simple user feedback.

00:17:00.479 --> 00:17:01.900
And you can start this during the early age

00:17:01.900 --> 00:17:02.780
of development.

00:17:02.780 --> 00:17:05.500
You don't need to wait until you've deployed the dashboard.

00:17:05.500 --> 00:17:07.239
You can iterate on this before problems

00:17:07.239 --> 00:17:09.300
even surface for your users.

00:17:11.300 --> 00:17:13.180
BID UX is currently available on CRAN,

00:17:13.180 --> 00:17:14.739
so installation is really simple.

00:17:14.739 --> 00:17:18.180
Just simply install and load the library,

00:17:18.180 --> 00:17:19.579
and then run through those five stages,

00:17:19.579 --> 00:17:21.060
because even with minimal input,

00:17:21.060 --> 00:17:23.300
you get valuable suggestions.

00:17:23.300 --> 00:17:26.579
And there's also a BID concepts function,

00:17:26.579 --> 00:17:28.900
so if you're unfamiliar with a function,

00:17:28.900 --> 00:17:29.739
you can explore that.

00:17:29.739 --> 00:17:31.739
It's kind of like having a psychological textbook

00:17:31.739 --> 00:17:32.739
right there on hand.

